Author-Name:    Shepard, Andrea
Title:   Price Discrimination and Retail Configuration. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 30-53
Issue: 1
Volume: 99
Year: 1991
Month:  February 
Abstract:
  The hypothesis that price discrimination based on willingness-to-pay for
 quality can occur in multifirm markets is confirmed using microdata on
 gasoline retailing. A test that discriminates between price structures
 associated with discrimination and with cost-driven, competitive
 differentials is developed and implemented with controls for variation in
 outlet and market characteristics. A second test based on profitability
 variation rejects a competitive, peak-load pricing explanation for the
 observed price dispersion. The data suggest that price discrimination at
 the retail level adds at least nine cents a gallon to the average price of
 full-service gasoline.  Copyright 1991 by University of Chicago Press.
